Making polygone maps in R

We use the Netherlands admin2 level in shape format, which can be downloaded We need to load the following libraries:

We load the map and print the empty map:

gemeente <- readShapeSpatial('NLD_adm2', proj4string = CRS("+init=epsg:27700"))
plot(gemeente)

Next we are going to define the regions to the polygones on the map.

data <- fortify(gemeente)
## Regions defined for each Polygons
# And lets show this zoomed in to the region of Utrecht
qmap('Utrecht', zoom = 10) + geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), data = data, colour = 'white', fill = 'black', alpha = .4, size = .3)
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=Utrecht&zoom=10&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&language=en-EN&sensor=false
## Information from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Utrecht&sensor=false

Population of the Netherlands

We are going to make coloured polygone map showing the population of the Netherlands.
We are going to use CBS data and map

library("gdata", lib.loc="~/R/win-library/3.3")
bev <- read.xls("bev.xls")
head(bev,5)
##        gemeente bevolking  X
## 1   Aa en Hunze     25541 NA
## 2       Aalburg     12774 NA
## 3      Aalsmeer     30618 NA
## 4        Aalten     27082 NA
## 5 Achtkarspelen     28110 NA
gemeente <- readShapeSpatial("gem_2013_v1")
map_id <- gemeente$GM_NAAM
gemeente <- fortify(gemeente, region = "GM_NAAM")
ggplot() + geom_map(data = bev, aes(map_id = gemeente, fill = bevolking), map = gemeente) + expand_limits(x = gemeente$long, y = gemeente$lat)

# now we save and print the map
p <- ggplot() + geom_map(data = bev, aes(map_id = gemeente, fill = bevolking), map = gemeente) + expand_limits(x = gemeente$long, y = gemeente$lat)
ggsave(p, file = "bev2.png", width = 6, height = 4.5, type = "cairo-png")

gkaart <- fortify(gkaart, region = "GM_CODE")
map_id <- gkaart$GM_CODE
ggplot() + geom_map(data = gdata, aes(map_id = CODE, fill = P_SURINAM), map = gkaart) + expand_limits(x = gkaart$long, y = gkaart$lat)

# example 2 WOZ taxes
ggplot() + geom_map(data = gdata, aes(map_id = CODE, fill = WOZ), map = gkaart) + expand_limits(x = gkaart$long, y = gkaart$lat)+ scale_fill_gradient2(low = "red",mid = "white", midpoint = 200, high ="blue", limits = c(0, 600)) 

# example 3 high incomes
ggplot() + geom_map(data = gdata, aes(map_id = CODE, fill = P_HOOGINKP), map = gkaart) + expand_limits(x = gkaart$long, y = gkaart$lat)+ scale_fill_gradient2(low = "red",mid = "white", midpoint = 25, high ="blue", limits = c(0, 50))

Remark

Note how the maps are merged: map_id(GM_CODE) is set to CODE in the data; and also midpoint and limits depend on the range of the data
